'''Anker''' is a brand of Chinese electronics company '''Anker Innovations''' (formerly '''Oceanwing''').<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/mobile/anker-innovations-eufy-roav-zolo-anker-nebula/|title=Anker Innovations’ six key sub-brands focus on smart home, batteries, and more|last=Chokkattu|first=Julian|date=2018-01-08|website=[[Digital Trends]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref> based in [[Shenzhen]], [[Guangdong]]. The brand is known for producing computer and mobile peripherals, especially [[Battery_charger#Power_bank|power bank]]s.
==History== [[File:AnkerAstro.jpg|thumb|''Anker Astro'', a mobile battery charger introduced in 2011]]Steven Yang started Anker in 2011 after working as software engineer for [[Google]] in [[California]]. He moved to [[Shenzhen]], China. In early 2012 ''Google'''s then-head of sales in China, Dongping Zhao, was hired and as of 2018 is president of ''Anker Innovations''.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/5/22/15673712/anker-battery-charger-amazon-empire-steven-yang-interview|title=How Anker is beating Apple and Samsung at their own accessory game|last=Staff|first=Nick|date=2017-05-22|website=[[The Verge]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-05-22}}</ref>
In 2012, Anker switched its focus from replacement laptop batteries to smartphone [[battery charger]]s and wall chargers.<ref name=":0" />
Anker maintains subsidiaries in [[California]], [[Germany]], the [[United Kingdom]], [[Japan]] and [[China]] as well as contractors in [[South Korea]], [[Kuwait]], [[Saudi Arabia]] and [[Romania]]. Before 2017 Anker devices were almost exclusively sold at [[Amazon Marketplace]].
==Products== Anker charging devices use its ''PowerIQ'' proprietary technology, which detects the connected device and automatically optimizes the [[Current source|current]] delivered, thereby reducing the amount of time for a device to reach full charge.<ref name=":0" /> Many of Anker's charging devices also use various fast-charging technologies, such as [[Quick Charge]]. Anker was mentioned in 2015 as the leading brand of mobile chargers on [[Amazon.com]].<ref name="internetretailer">{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalcommerce360.com/2015/10/03/how-chinese-startup-became-top-seller-amazoncom/|title=How a Chinese startup became a top seller on Amazon.com|publisher=internetretailer.com|accessdate=2017-05-28}}</ref>
Outside of its core competency, Anker also incorporates other product lines: * ''Eufy'' (smart home appliances, since September 2016)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/09/14/eufy/|title=Anker launches sister brand for home automation|last=Kamps|first=Haje Jan|website=TechCrunch|access-date=2017-05-24}}</ref> * ''Soundcore'' (headphones and portable speakers) * ''Zolo'' (headphones and portable speakers, since 2018) * ''Nebula'' (portable [[video projector]]s) * ''Roav'' (car accessories)
==Controversies== In 2014, an [[Indiegogo]] campaign to promote a set of magnetic accessories called ''Zolo'' was launched.<ref name="indiegogo">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/zolo-a-magnetic-case-battery-cable-system--2#/|publisher=indiegogo.com|title=Zolo: A Magnetic Case, Battery &amp; Cable System &#124; Indiegogo|accessdate=2016-11-06}}</ref> Due to prolonged manufacturing challenges the project was set on hold and 1863 backers were offered a 200% refund.
In 2016, a batch of Anker USB-C charging cables suffered a manufacturing defect that could potentially cause damage to connected hardware, leading to a recall.<ref name="The Register">{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2016/08/30/anker_usbc_cables_recalled#/|publisher=TheRegister.com|title=Ankers away! USB-C cables recalled over freakin' fried phone fears|accessdate=2017-02-01}}</ref>
